`ComponentDidUpdate` will let you see if a prop changed:

**Parent:**
```javascript
constructor(props) {
  super(props);
  this.state = {
    gotData: false;
  }
}

handleOnClick {
  this.setState({ gotData: false });
  this.apiService.getData(() =&gt; {
    // ...
    this.setState({ gotData: true });
  }
}

// render()
&lt;Child onClick={handleOnClick} gotData={this.state.gotData} /&gt;
```


**Child:**
```javascript
componentDidUpdate(prevProps) {
  if (props.gotData &amp;&amp; props.gotData !== prevProps.gotData) {
    alert(&#39;data came in! (child)&#39;);
  }
}
```

Assuming your API request is not immediate/way too fast, gotData will be first set to false. Then, when the API response comes back, gotData gets set to true and is different from the previous gotData, hence triggering the `alert` code.

In real-life/bigger applications, instead of gotData, usually the response from the network, in the form of an `id` or a Redux state update is used, but this should work for your case.

Hope it&#39;s more clear now!

